## 3. Database Layer

### Prisma Model

```prisma
// packages/db-main-prisma/prisma/postgres/schema.prisma  (line 906)
model ChatFile {
  id          String    @id @default(cuid())
  token       String    @unique          // MinIO presign token; used as the context reference key
  name        String
  size        BigInt                     // stored as BIGINT; serialised to Number on read
  mimetype    String
  path        String                     // object path inside the private bucket, e.g. "chat-file/abc123"
  baseId      String    @map("base_id") // scopes the file to a base
  createdBy   String    @map("created_by")
  createdTime DateTime  @default(now()) @map("created_time")
  deletedTime DateTime? @map("deleted_time")  // null = active; non-null = soft-deleted

  @@index([baseId])
  @@map("chat_file")
}
```

### Migration

```sql
-- packages/db-main-prisma/prisma/postgres/migrations/20260514000000_add_chat_file/migration.sql
CREATE TABLE "chat_file" (
    "id"           TEXT         NOT NULL,
    "token"        TEXT         NOT NULL,
    "name"         TEXT         NOT NULL,
    "size"         BIGINT       NOT NULL,
    "mimetype"     TEXT         NOT NULL,
    "path"         TEXT         NOT NULL,
    "base_id"      TEXT         NOT NULL,
    "created_by"   TEXT         NOT NULL,
    "created_time" TIMESTAMP(3) NOT NULL DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,
    "deleted_time" TIMESTAMP(3),
    CONSTRAINT "chat_file_pkey" PRIMARY KEY ("id")
);
CREATE UNIQUE INDEX "chat_file_token_key"   ON "chat_file"("token");
CREATE INDEX        "chat_file_base_id_idx" ON "chat_file"("base_id");
```

**Why `token` is unique and indexed**: the token issued by the presign endpoint is the immutable identity of a file across the system. It appears in the AI request payload as the opaque reference. The unique constraint prevents the same upload being registered twice.

**Why `deletedTime` instead of hard delete**: soft delete preserves audit history and guards against concurrent delete-then-read races during AI context extraction. A file being extracted by the AI service won't vanish mid-read.

**Why `size` is `BIGINT`**: PostgreSQL's `INTEGER` (32-bit) overflows at ~2 GB. BigInt is stored natively. The service converts it to a JS `Number` before returning to the client; files are capped at 10 MB so the value always fits safely in a 64-bit float.

