## 11. File Type Handling

### Allowed Types

Enforced at **both** client (MIME check + `accept` attribute) and server (`saveFile` validation).

| MIME Type | Extension(s) | Extraction Method |
|-----------|-------------|-------------------|
| `application/pdf` | `.pdf` | `pdf-parse(buffer).text` |
| `application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.wordprocessingml.document` | `.docx` | `mammoth.extractRawText({ buffer }).value` |
| `application/msword` | `.doc` | `mammoth.extractRawText({ buffer }).value` |
| `text/plain` | `.txt` | `buffer.toString('utf-8')` |
| `text/markdown` | `.md` | `buffer.toString('utf-8')` |
| `text/html` | `.html`, `.htm` | `buffer.toString('utf-8')` |
| `text/csv` | `.csv` | `buffer.toString('utf-8')` |

**Size limit**: 10 MB. Validated client-side first (fast feedback), then server-side in `saveFile` (authoritative guard).

### Why `pdf-parse` and `mammoth` Are Lazy-Required

Both libraries are heavy (C extension bindings, large WASM bundles). Loading them at module startup would increase cold-start time for every request. `require()` inside the MIME-type branch loads them once on first use and caches them in Node's module registry, paying the cost only when a PDF or Word file actually needs parsing.

### Why Text Types Are Returned as Raw UTF-8

HTML, CSV, and Markdown are text-serialisable by definition. The LLM handles HTML tags and CSV delimiters well enough for typical document Q&A. Adding a parsing step (strip tags, parse rows) would require additional dependencies and would risk losing structural cues the model might find useful. `extractTextFromFile` is the single extension point if richer extraction is needed for a specific type.

